    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nLua errors are quite verbose, much more than Vimscript/C-core errors:\n\n```\nError in /Users/yochem/Library/Config/nvim/init.lua:\nE5113: Lua chunk: /Users/yochem/Library/Config/nvim/init.lua:324: problem here!\nstack traceback:\n\t[C]: in function 'error'\n\t/Users/yochem/Library/Config/nvim/init.lua:324: in main chunk\n```\n\nEven with ui2, the traceback is noisy for regular users.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI propose `error()` (and `assert()`) respect `'verbose'` and only show the traceback when 'verbose' > 0. Maybe the following format can be used when 'verbose' is 0:\n\n```\nE5113: Error at ~/Library/Config/nvim/init.lua:324: problem here!\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Vimscript `throw` shows a stacktrace. Whereas `:echoerr` is more like `vim.notify(...,{level=ERROR})`, in spirit?\n\nI am not really sure this gains anything. If ui2 needs to be improved, or if the first line of Lua errors can be improved, then we should do that.\n\nThough as a side-note, I do think `verbose=1` should be the entrypoint for more stuff.\n\n> Even with ui2, the traceback is noisy for regular users.\n\nIt is (should be) only shown if they expand it...",
